{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510960"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:35:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:35:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11666"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11666"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.16,0.16,0.06,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4287"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80582"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4287"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65873"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1634"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5783"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6148"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9886"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26969"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80582"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year old man presents to the Emergency Department following a professional mixed martial arts competition. His left leg was repeatedly kicked on the lateral aspect, just inferior to the knee. Following the competition, he was struggling to walk and complained of numbness of his foot. There was no significant head trauma or loss of consciousness. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EOn examination, there is a unilateral \u0027high steppage\u0027 gate. He is unable to dorsiflex and evert his left foot, and there is also reduced extension of the digits. There is significant sensation loss over the left dorsum, between the hallux and second digit, and the anterolateral aspect of the leg is observed. The rest of the lower limb neurological examination was normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely nerve to be injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sciatic nerve","Superficial peroneal nerve","Deep peroneal nerve","Tibial nerve","Common peroneal nerve"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a characteristic case of \u0022foot drop\u0022 due to injury of the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommon peroneal nerve \u003C/strong\u003E(also known as the common fibular nerve). The common peroneal nerve runs superficially around the head of the fibula giving rise to the \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperficial and deep peroneal nerves. \u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESuperficial peroneal nerve (L5, S1, S2) \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMotor: innervates the muscles of the lateral compartment of the leg (fibularis longus and brevis). These muscles act to evert the foot and weakly plantarflex the ankle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensory: supplies skin of the anterolateral leg, dorsum of foot and all digits (except the skin between the first and second digits).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDeep peroneal nerve (L4, L5) \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMotor: innervates the muscles of the anterior compartment of the leg (tibialis anterior, extensor digitorum longus and extensor hallucis longus). These muscles act to dorsiflex the ankle, invert foot and extend the digits. It also innervates two intrinsic muscles of the foot (extensor digitorum brevis and extensor hallucis brevis) that act to extend digits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensory: Supplies skin or \u0027web space\u0027 between the first and second digits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDorsiflexion and extension of the digits are impaired in this case, indicating an injury to the deep peroneal nerve. Inability to evert the foot indicates an injury to the superficial peroneal nerve. The patient hyperflexes the thigh at the hip to ensure clearance of the foot drop (resulting from the inability to dorsiflex), known as a \u0027high steppage gait\u0027. The distribution of sensory loss also indicates the involvement of both nerves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA nerve palsy of the common peroneal nerve, affecting both downstream superficial and deep peroneal nerves, explains the findings. The mechanism of injury is also consistent with a common peroneal nerve palsy due to its superficial course. An X-ray should be ordered to exclude a fracture to the head of the fibula.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esciatic nerve \u003C/strong\u003Einnervates muscles of the posterior thigh, allowing for flexion of the knee. The \u003Cstrong\u003Etibial nerve \u003C/strong\u003Einnervates muscles of the posterior leg, allowing for plantarflexion and inversion of the ankle, alongside flexion of the digits. Skin innervation involves the posterolateral leg and lateral and sole aspects of the foot. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The common peroneal nerve runs around the head of the fibula, giving rise to the superficial and deep peroneal nerves.","Injury to the common peroneal nerve can result in foot drop, characterised by an inability to dorsiflex the foot and a high steppage gait."],"references":["Elkwood AI, Schneider LF, Rose MI. Lower extremity. In: Rehabilitative Surgery: A Comprehensive Text for an Emerging Field, Elkwood AI, Kaufman M, Schneider LF (Eds), Springer, Cham, Switzerland 2017. Available from:  10.1007/978-3-319-41406-5","Hansen LT. Lower limb. In: Netter\u0027s Clinical Anatomy, 4th ed, Hansen LT, Netter FH, Machado CAG (Eds), Elsevier, Philadelphia 2018.","Poage C, Roth C, Scott B. Peroneal Nerve Palsy: Evaluation and Management. J Am Acad Orthop Surg. 2016 Jan;24(1):1-10. doi: 10.5435/JAAOS-D-14-00420. PMID: 26700629. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26700629/","Lezak B, Massel DH, Varacallo MA. Peroneal Nerve Injury. [Updated 2024 Feb 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK549859/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65873"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11666"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65873"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-21T17:13:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-21T17:14:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4287"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80582"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description"